            "id": "155e215c27ba4a78ab818",
            "questionText": "An engineer is designing an electron microscope. To enhance the resolution for nanoscale imaging, they accelerate electrons through a potential difference of $!$150 V$!$. Given that the electron's mass is approximately $!$9.109 \\times 10^{-31} kg$!$ and its charge is $!$1.602 \\times 10^{-19} C$!$, calculate the de Broglie wavelength of these electrons. This wavelength will determine the microscope's ability to resolve fine details. Use Planck's constant, $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} Js$!$, for your calculations.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "a9d93c4235c84b40a8ed4",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the core concept that relates a particle's momentum to its wavelength. Please choose the correct de Broglie relation from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6ebe6c0d-c162-454d-9895-d18bb1afb5b9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h}{p}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = h \\cdot p$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{p}{h}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "384bae253fb4427b98c9a",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, considering that electrons accelerated by a potential difference gain kinetic energy, which formula correctly expresses the de Broglie wavelength in terms of the accelerating potential $!$V$!$? Select the appropriate relation.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2fc1331f-b464-447e-aaa9-e1806d7e9191"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{2m e V}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h}{2m e V}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\sqrt{\\frac{h}{2m e V}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "640ffd2ce7c5444f99289",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Now, let\u2019s compute the intermediate value inside the square root: calculate $!$2 \\times m \\times e \\times V$!$. Using $!$m=9.109\\times10^{-31} kg$!$, $!$e=1.602\\times10^{-19} C$!$, and $!$V=150 V$!$, what is the numerical value of this product?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.377e-47"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2fc1331f-b464-447e-aaa9-e1806d7e9191"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "42525316794542c6b8594",
                    "stepText": "Finally, apply the de Broglie formula by dividing Planck's constant $!$h=6.626\\times10^{-34} Js$!$ by the square root of the value from the previous step to determine the electron's wavelength. What is the computed de Broglie wavelength in meters?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.0e-10"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6ebe6c0d-c162-454d-9895-d18bb1afb5b9",
                        "2fc1331f-b464-447e-aaa9-e1806d7e9191"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "3c6215007fa54b2182184",
            "questionText": "In a medical imaging facility, X-rays with an initial wavelength of $!$0.075 nm$!$ are used to scan a patient's bones. Some photons undergo Compton scattering with electrons and are scattered at an angle of $!$110^{\\circ}$!$ relative to their original direction. Using the constants $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} Js$!$, $!$m_e = 9.109 \\times 10^{-31} kg$!$, and $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 m/s$!$, calculate the final wavelength of the scattered X-ray photons.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "b65db1d9172b4e21b4bc7",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula that represents the change in wavelength in Compton scattering. Which of the following formulas do you think is the appropriate one?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "254b2a82-f030-41e6-beba-8436ce763d64"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\lambda = \\frac{h}{m_e c}(1 - \\cos\\theta)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\lambda = \\frac{h}{m_e c}(\\cos\\theta - 1)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\lambda = \\frac{h}{c}(1 - \\cos\\theta)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "8cb617fd364149bf910f1",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, calculate the Compton wavelength $!$\\lambda_C = \\frac{h}{m_e c}$!$ using the provided constants. Enter the numerical value you obtain (in meters).",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.43e-12"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "c1d907e9-f018-4c16-a6ee-4946975d59c2"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "8115a8a0110d49f299fa4",
                    "stepText": "Now, compute the factor $!$(1 - \\cos\\theta)$!$ for the scattering angle of $!$110^{\\circ}$!$. Remember to evaluate the cosine correctly, and then subtract it from 1.",
